1
00:00:04,600 --> 00:00:05,640
(GROWLING)

2
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:07,320
-DOCTOR: Start the clock.
-(CLOCK TICKING)

3
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:14,400
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

4
00:00:19,240 --> 00:00:22,520
Is there some sort of fancy dress thing
on this evening?

5
00:00:23,240 --> 00:00:25,360
I don't think so. Why do you ask?

6
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:27,400
Well, that fellow over there,

7
00:00:27,520 --> 00:00:29,880
dressed as a mummy monster thing.

8
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:31,880
Who do you mean? I can't see him.

9
00:00:33,640 --> 00:00:35,120
Um, you!

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,320
You! Throw that man
out of my dining car.

11
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:40,640
It's disgusting.

12
00:00:40,720 --> 00:00:42,640
I'm sorry, madam. Which man?

13
00:00:42,720 --> 00:00:45,120
Which man? I'll have your job.

14
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:48,280
That man, right there,
dressed as a monster.

15
00:00:50,120 --> 00:00:53,240
Mama, there isn't anyone there.
Are you feeling okay?

16
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:55,600
Don't you dare lie to me, girl.

17
00:00:56,240 --> 00:00:57,960
I won't be made a fool of.

18
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:00,800
Stop it. Stop it.

19
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:02,680
Stop him at once. Right now.

20
00:01:02,880 --> 00:01:04,280
Mama, there's no one there.

21
00:01:04,360 --> 00:01:06,600
You're worrying me.
Do you want one of your pills?

22
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:09,760
Not a step further. Oh, no! Get it off!

23
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:12,000
Oh, no, get it off!

24
00:01:14,160 --> 00:01:17,360
Oh! Is there a doctor?
Sorry, I need... I need a doctor!

25
00:01:17,440 --> 00:01:19,960
(STAMMERING) Sorry, I don't know,
she just stopped.

26
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:26,160
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

27
00:01:28,720 --> 00:01:30,480
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

28
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:05,800
(WHOOSHING)

29
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:15,640
Your train awaits, my lady.

30
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:19,240
Wonderful.

31
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:22,200
The baggage car.

32
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:23,800
But thanks for lying.

33
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:27,200
The real wonderful is through here.

34
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:29,600
(TRAIN BELL JINGLES)

35
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:35,120
There were many trains
to take the name Orient Express,

36
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,320
but only one

37
00:02:39,960 --> 00:02:41,880
in space!

38
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:45,320
Of course it is.

39
00:02:45,720 --> 00:02:47,520
WOMAN: # So don't stop me now

40
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:50,640
Completely faithful recreation
of the original Orient Express.

41
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:53,360
Except slightly bigger. And in space.

42
00:02:53,440 --> 00:02:55,480
Oh, and the rails
are actually hyperspace ribbons.

43
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,880
-But in every other respect identical.
-# Because I'm having a good time

44
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:01,520
Painstaking attention to detail.

45
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:05,080
Most of the time.

46
00:03:05,400 --> 00:03:09,080
# on a collision course
I'm a satellite

47
00:03:09,240 --> 00:03:10,800
# I'm out of control

48
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:14,080
# I'm a sex machine ready to reload

49
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:16,080
# Like an atom bomb

50
00:03:16,160 --> 00:03:18,120
# I'm 'bout to oh, oh, oh

51
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:20,640
-You're doing it again.
-Doing what?

52
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:22,320
-The smile.
-(CHUCKLES) Yeah, I'm smiling.

53
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:24,160
Yeah, it's the sad smile.

54
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:26,320
It's a smile but you're sad.

55
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:28,560
It's confusing.
It's like two emotions at once.

56
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:31,040
-It's like you're malfunctioning.
-Sorry.

57
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:34,200
# I'm travelling at the speed of light

58
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:37,720
# I'm gonna make
a supersonic man out of you

59
00:03:38,720 --> 00:03:40,280
I just thought that this would be
a good one to...

60
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:42,560
To end it? Yeah.

61
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:46,160
It is. It's a good choice.

62
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:47,360
Good one to end on.

63
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:48,800
-Yeah?
-Mmm-hmm.

64
00:03:48,880 --> 00:03:50,760
# If you wanna have a good time

65
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:51,840
-Shall we?
-Mmm-hmm.

66
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,320
# Just give me a call
Oh, don't stop me now

67
00:03:57,440 --> 00:03:58,960
# Don't stop me... #

68
00:03:59,080 --> 00:04:00,120
(BELL DINGS)

69
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:03,120
MAN: Ladies and gentlemen,
if you would be good enough

70
00:04:03,200 --> 00:04:05,520
to look from the windows
on the right of the train,

71
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:06,600
you'll be able to see

72
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:09,840
the soaring majesty
of the Magellan black hole.

73
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:13,840
Ah, I remember when this was all planets
as far as the eye could see.

74
00:04:15,800 --> 00:04:17,080
All gone now.

75
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:19,400
Gobbled up by that beast.

76
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:24,280
And there's that smile again.
I don't even know how you do that.

77
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,800
I really thought I hated you, you know?

78
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:30,680
Well, thank God
you kept that to yourself.

79
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:32,960
There was this planet, Obsidian.

80
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:35,760
-Planet of perpetual darkness.
-I did.

81
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:38,600
I did hate you.
In fact, I hated you for weeks.

82
00:04:38,680 --> 00:04:40,160
Good, fine.
I'm glad that we cleared that up.

83
00:04:40,240 --> 00:04:42,920
But there was also a planet
that was made completely of shrubs.

84
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:44,680
-I went to a concert once.
-(SIGHS)

85
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:47,280
Can't remember who it was.
But do you know what the singer said?

86
00:04:47,360 --> 00:04:49,720
Well, frankly, that would be
an absolutely astonishing guess

87
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:51,800
-if I did know.
-She said,

88
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,800
"Hatred is too strong an emotion to
waste on someone that you don't like."

89
00:05:00,080 --> 00:05:01,840
Were people really confused?
'Cause I'm confused.

90
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:03,720
-Did everybody leave?
-Shut up.

91
00:05:04,840 --> 00:05:05,840
(SIGHS)

92
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:09,240
Look, what I'm trying to say is

93
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:11,200
I don't hate you.

94
00:05:12,600 --> 00:05:14,600
I could never hate you.

95
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:19,720
But I can't do this any more,
not the way you do it.

96
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:27,560
Can I talk about the planets now?

97
00:05:27,640 --> 00:05:29,200
Yes.

98
00:05:31,280 --> 00:05:32,280
Go!

99
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:34,720
Thedion Four, constant acid rain.

100
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:37,080
Had a lovely picnic there once,
wearing a gas mask.

101
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:38,360
That's a lie.

102
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:41,600
I'm sorry?

103
00:05:42,120 --> 00:05:44,240
That's a lie, what you said.

104
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,880
Thedion Four was destroyed
thousands of years ago,

105
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:48,160
so you couldn't have been there.

106
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:52,200
Miss Pitt, are you sure
you wouldn't rather rest in your room?

107
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:53,840
That man's a liar.

108
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:58,160
Perhaps you'd allow
Mr Carlyle here to escort you back.

109
00:05:58,960 --> 00:06:02,040
MR CARLYLE: It'll be all right, Miss.
Just come with me.

110
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:05,960
Sorry about that.

111
00:06:06,040 --> 00:06:09,040
I suppose it's understandable
in the circumstances.

112
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:12,160
I don't believe we've been introduced.

113
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:13,280
Captain Quell.

114
00:06:13,400 --> 00:06:15,200
I'm Clara. This is the Doctor.

115
00:06:15,280 --> 00:06:17,080
CAPTAIN: Ah, another one.

116
00:06:17,160 --> 00:06:18,160
Sorry? Another what?

117
00:06:18,360 --> 00:06:22,160
Well, we've got doctors and professors
coming out of our ears on this trip.

118
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,040
So, what are you a doctor of?

119
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:26,920
Now, there's a question
that's never asked often enough.

120
00:06:27,280 --> 00:06:28,640
Let's say

121
00:06:28,720 --> 00:06:30,600
intestinal parasites.

122
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:34,280
I'm beginning to think
Miss Pitt was right about you.

123
00:06:37,440 --> 00:06:40,360
What's wrong with her?
Did something happen?

124
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,520
You mean, you really don't know?

125
00:06:44,760 --> 00:06:47,040
There's a body and there's a mummy.

126
00:06:47,280 --> 00:06:48,680
I mean, can you not just get on a train?

127
00:06:48,760 --> 00:06:50,560
Did a wizard put a curse on you
about mini-breaks?

128
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:52,200
Might be nothing.
Old ladies die all the time.

129
00:06:52,280 --> 00:06:53,760
It's practically their job description.

130
00:06:53,840 --> 00:06:54,840
And the monster?

131
00:06:55,320 --> 00:06:57,200
Well, seen by no one except her,

132
00:06:57,280 --> 00:06:58,920
which suggests that it wasn't there.

133
00:06:59,080 --> 00:07:01,040
Dying brain, lack of oxygen,
hallucinations.

134
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:03,120
Anyway, people do just die sometimes.

135
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:04,600
She was over 100 years old.

136
00:07:04,760 --> 00:07:06,440
Says the 2,000-year-old man.

137
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:09,280
Clara, you actually sound as if
you want this to be a thing.

138
00:07:09,360 --> 00:07:10,560
Do you?

139
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:11,960
No.

140
00:07:12,040 --> 00:07:13,560
No, look, fine.

141
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:15,760
You know, if you think
that there is nothing to worry about,

142
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:17,000
then that is fine by me.

143
00:07:17,080 --> 00:07:18,880
-Are you sure?
-Ah, yes, I'm sure.

144
00:07:23,120 --> 00:07:24,960
To our last hurrah.

145
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,280
Oh, last, yeah.

146
00:07:28,360 --> 00:07:30,960
But I mean, it's not like
I'm never going to see you again.

147
00:07:31,040 --> 00:07:32,120
Isn't it?

148
00:07:33,600 --> 00:07:34,600
Is it?

149
00:07:35,360 --> 00:07:37,280
I thought that's what you wanted.

150
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:41,400
No, well, I mean, you know,
you're going to come round

151
00:07:41,480 --> 00:07:43,520
for dinner or something, aren't you?
Do you do that?

152
00:07:43,600 --> 00:07:45,360
Do you come round
to people's houses for dinner?

153
00:07:46,880 --> 00:07:48,160
Of course. Why wouldn't I do that?

154
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:50,600
I don't know.
I thought you might find it boring.

155
00:07:50,680 --> 00:07:52,080
-Is it boring?
-No.

156
00:07:58,760 --> 00:08:00,120
To the last hurrah.

157
00:08:01,560 --> 00:08:02,760
The last hurrah.

158
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:12,320
(SIGHS)

159
00:08:12,840 --> 00:08:14,800
It's nothing. Nothing.

160
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,160
Definitely sure,

161
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:17,920
99% sure.

162
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:20,320
Really? 99%?

163
00:08:20,520 --> 00:08:21,600
That's quite high.

164
00:08:21,880 --> 00:08:23,320
Is that the figure you're sticking with?

165
00:08:23,600 --> 00:08:26,360
Okay, okay. Seventy-five.

166
00:08:27,120 --> 00:08:30,400
Well, that's jumped quite a bit.
You've just lost 24%.

167
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:33,360
DANNY: A train in space.

168
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:35,080
-Sounds pretty cool.
-So what are you saying?

169
00:08:35,160 --> 00:08:36,320
Just because he's brought me
somewhere cool,

170
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:37,560
I shouldn't dump him?

171
00:08:37,680 --> 00:08:40,360
Well, one, you can't dump him
because he's not your boyfriend

172
00:08:40,440 --> 00:08:43,920
and two, dumping him sounds
a little scorched-earth.

173
00:08:44,280 --> 00:08:45,920
You still basically get on.

174
00:08:46,320 --> 00:08:50,480
I think you should just enjoy
your space train.

175
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,640
At least it's not dangerous.

176
00:08:55,520 --> 00:08:58,360
Yeah. It's pretty...

177
00:08:58,440 --> 00:08:59,840
boring, really.

178
00:08:59,960 --> 00:09:01,720
Because you know
what this sounds like, don't you?

179
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:03,400
No, do tell me.

180
00:09:03,720 --> 00:09:06,000
A mummy that only the victim can see.

181
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:07,640
I was being rhetorical.

182
00:09:07,920 --> 00:09:10,200
I know exactly what this sounds like.

183
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,480
(WHISPERING) Doctor, are you awake?

184
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:47,280
(WHIRRING)

185
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:51,760
Beautiful bit of kit, isn't it, sir?

186
00:09:52,520 --> 00:09:55,240
The Excelsior Life Extender.

187
00:09:56,240 --> 00:09:58,840
It's like driving around
in a portable hospital.

188
00:09:58,920 --> 00:10:01,120
Yes, well, it didn't do Mrs Pitt
much good, did it?

189
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:03,040
Mmm. Got me there, sir.

190
00:10:03,480 --> 00:10:05,000
Certainly got me there.

191
00:10:05,920 --> 00:10:07,160
Maybe it malfunctioned.

192
00:10:07,240 --> 00:10:08,560
Oh, I don't think so.

193
00:10:09,160 --> 00:10:12,720
The records show that the machine did
everything it could to keep her alive.

194
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:16,280
Yeah. And almost
drained the battery doing it.

195
00:10:17,480 --> 00:10:18,720
What do you know?

196
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:22,800
Well, I know that when I find a man

197
00:10:22,920 --> 00:10:25,280
fiddling with a chair
that someone died in,

198
00:10:25,360 --> 00:10:28,480
it's best to play my cards
close to my chest.

199
00:10:28,640 --> 00:10:29,840
Really?

200
00:10:30,040 --> 00:10:31,440
Well, I know that when I find a man

201
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:34,120
loitering near a chair
that someone died in,

202
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:35,520
I do just the same.

203
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:39,600
Perkins.

204
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:41,040
Chief Engineer.

205
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:42,480
The Doctor.

206
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:44,720
Nosy Parker. (CHUCKLES)

207
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:47,480
Pleased to meet you, Doctor.

208
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:54,760
Course, there's a rumour that someone
or something else might be responsible.

209
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:02,560
Hello?

210
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:04,120
Are you okay?

211
00:11:07,640 --> 00:11:09,840
Hello? Excuse me?

212
00:11:11,680 --> 00:11:12,720
Excuse me?

213
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:15,200
Miss Pitt, wasn't it?

214
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:17,360
Are you all right?
Do you need some help?

215
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:19,480
My name's Maisie. I'm not mad.

216
00:11:20,520 --> 00:11:24,520
Oh, okay. Um, I didn't say you were.
But you've had a bad day.

217
00:11:24,920 --> 00:11:27,520
I think anybody could do with a little
bit of help after a day like today.

218
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:29,520
Computer, open the door.

219
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:30,760
MECHANICAL VOICE: Gall me Gus.

220
00:11:30,840 --> 00:11:34,760
I'm afraid this door can only be opened
by executive order.

221
00:11:37,280 --> 00:11:38,920
Are you... Are you okay?

222
00:11:39,080 --> 00:11:40,240
(SOBBING)

223
00:11:41,480 --> 00:11:43,120
They won't let me see her body.

224
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:45,240
They should let me see her body,
shouldn't they?

225
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:47,840
Uh, yeah, I should think so.
It's in there, is it?

226
00:11:47,920 --> 00:11:50,760
Okay, I have a friend
who's really good with locks.

227
00:11:51,040 --> 00:11:52,880
Do you want to come with me,
see if we can find him?

228
00:11:53,240 --> 00:11:54,240
(GRUNTS)

229
00:11:54,320 --> 00:11:55,320
Ooh!

230
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:59,520
Or you could do that
because that works, too.

231
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:03,240
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

232
00:12:09,160 --> 00:12:11,600
What's the most interesting thing
about the Foretold?

233
00:12:12,320 --> 00:12:13,760
I'm terribly sorry,
I don't believe we've met.

234
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:16,680
You know, the Foretold, mythical mummy.

235
00:12:16,760 --> 00:12:19,440
Legend has it that if you see it,
you're a dead man.

236
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:21,920
Yes, I know what it is.
You see, I happen to be...

237
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:23,600
Emil Moorhouse,
professor of alien mythology.

238
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:24,880
I'm the Doctor. Pleased to meet you.

239
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:27,920
So the most interesting thing
about the Foretold. Go!

240
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:31,000
Uh, well, it would have
to be the time limit

241
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:32,680
given before it kills you.

242
00:12:33,120 --> 00:12:35,360
I can't think of another myth
where it's so specific.

243
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:36,840
How does it go? Um...

244
00:12:37,160 --> 00:12:38,800
The number of evil twice over.

245
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:44,000
They that bear the Foretold's stare
have 66 seconds to live.

246
00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:45,920
No, no, no. Nice try. Very atmospheric.

247
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:47,320
But that's not it. Try again.

248
00:12:47,480 --> 00:12:49,960
A cynical man might say that you were
trying to pump me for information.

249
00:12:50,040 --> 00:12:51,040
(SCOFFS)

250
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:56,600
The myth of the Foretold
first appeared over 5,000 years ago.

251
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,960
In some stories,
there is a riddle or secret word

252
00:13:00,040 --> 00:13:01,480
that is supposed to make it stop.

253
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:03,920
Some characters try to bargain with it,

254
00:13:04,360 --> 00:13:08,560
offer riches, confess sins.
All to no avail.

255
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:13,800
Well, you certainly know
a little mythology.

256
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:15,320
I know a lot.

257
00:13:15,640 --> 00:13:18,200
Because from time to time,
it turns out to be true.

258
00:13:21,520 --> 00:13:23,960
CHEF 1: What's that?
CHEF 2: What?

259
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:25,080
CHEF 1: What is that?

260
00:13:25,560 --> 00:13:27,480
But that's the great appeal, isn't it?

261
00:13:28,400 --> 00:13:30,960
-You can't see him?
-Earth legends are such dry,

262
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:32,960
dusty affairs and always fiction.

263
00:13:33,040 --> 00:13:34,680
But up here, in the stars,

264
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:36,600
-anything's possible.
-Get it away!

265
00:13:37,040 --> 00:13:38,560
MOORHOUSE: That's why I chose
this field, to be honest,

266
00:13:38,640 --> 00:13:41,200
hoping one day
I might meet a real monster.

267
00:13:41,840 --> 00:13:43,600
Isn't that everyone's dream?

268
00:13:43,680 --> 00:13:45,280
But you still haven't
answered my riddle.

269
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:47,480
What's the most interesting thing
about the Foretold?

270
00:13:47,560 --> 00:13:49,720
Well, you can't run from it,
that's for sure.

271
00:13:49,800 --> 00:13:52,120
There are accounts of people trying
but it never works.

272
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:54,280
No matter how far you run,
it's always right there behind you.

273
00:13:54,360 --> 00:13:56,360
-There's nothing there!
-There's nothing there.

274
00:13:56,440 --> 00:13:58,280
-Can't you see it?
-Calm down.

275
00:13:58,360 --> 00:14:01,240
-Get it away! Get it away!
-CHEF 3: What's wrong with him?

276
00:14:02,080 --> 00:14:04,080
-Get it away! Get it away!
-No.

277
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:09,160
Get it away! Get it away!

278
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:12,360
CHEF 2: What is going on?
CHEF 3: Stumpy, open the door.

279
00:14:12,440 --> 00:14:14,880
-CHEF 2: Open the door!
-(CLOCK TICKING)

280
00:14:15,520 --> 00:14:16,520
(HISSING)

281
00:14:18,120 --> 00:14:19,360
(GASPS)

282
00:14:19,600 --> 00:14:20,600
He's unhinged!

283
00:14:22,200 --> 00:14:23,200
(SCREAMS)

284
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:28,600
No! Stumpy!

285
00:14:28,720 --> 00:14:30,120
DOCTOR: Nope. Even colder.

286
00:14:30,280 --> 00:14:33,560
-All right, I give up, you tell me.
-Mrs Pitt, the old woman who died.

287
00:14:33,640 --> 00:14:35,480
She died of old age.
Nothing supernatural.

288
00:14:35,560 --> 00:14:36,840
No. That's my answer.

289
00:14:36,920 --> 00:14:37,920
Her death?

290
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,720
No. The fact that you were here
to witness it.

291
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:42,120
Excuse me, Professor.

292
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:45,000
(ALARMED CHATTERING, INDISTINCT)

293
00:14:48,400 --> 00:14:49,720
CAPTAIN: It was a heart attack.

294
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,720
And if I hear anyone spreading rumours
to the contrary,

295
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:54,080
they'll be getting off
at the next station,

296
00:14:54,160 --> 00:14:56,360
termination papers in hand.
Are we clear?

297
00:14:59,280 --> 00:15:01,040
-Do you know what you're doing?
-Nope.

298
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:04,360
But I do need to be slightly
more skilled than a high-heeled shoe.

299
00:15:04,440 --> 00:15:05,720
(CHUCKLES)

300
00:15:06,600 --> 00:15:07,840
-Oh.
-Mmm.

301
00:15:08,320 --> 00:15:11,000
Do you ever wish bad things on people?

302
00:15:11,120 --> 00:15:12,960
Oh, yeah. All the time.

303
00:15:13,040 --> 00:15:15,120
Whoever designed this door, for a start.

304
00:15:15,320 --> 00:15:16,880
She wasn't really my mum.

305
00:15:17,280 --> 00:15:19,840
She just made me call her that.
She was my gran.

306
00:15:21,400 --> 00:15:23,440
Do you know why I wanted
to see her body?

307
00:15:26,560 --> 00:15:29,920
Because you loved her very much
and were missing her?

308
00:15:30,080 --> 00:15:32,880
(LAUGHS) You obviously never met her.

309
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:35,720
No, I just felt really guilty.

310
00:15:36,760 --> 00:15:38,880
Like I'd been picturing her dying
for years.

311
00:15:38,960 --> 00:15:40,320
Like a daydream.

312
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:43,360
Not really meaning it.
At least, I don't think I did.

313
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:49,280
But now, it just feels like
I made this happen.

314
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:54,040
Hey, listen,

315
00:15:55,040 --> 00:15:56,200
you didn't do anything wrong.

316
00:15:56,280 --> 00:15:59,840
Difficult people,
they can make you feel

317
00:16:00,160 --> 00:16:01,720
all sorts of things.

318
00:16:02,680 --> 00:16:05,040
But you didn't do it.
You didn't kill her.

319
00:16:05,120 --> 00:16:07,480
She just died.

320
00:16:08,120 --> 00:16:09,880
Are you sure about that?

321
00:16:19,840 --> 00:16:21,280
I think we need to talk.

322
00:16:21,560 --> 00:16:24,000
This matter does not
concern the passengers.

323
00:16:24,080 --> 00:16:25,600
I'm not a passenger.

324
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:28,480
I'm your worst nightmare.

325
00:16:30,360 --> 00:16:32,520
A mystery shopper. Oh, great.

326
00:16:32,680 --> 00:16:34,320
Really? That's your worst...

327
00:16:34,640 --> 00:16:36,320
Okay, I'm a mystery shopper.

328
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:37,520
I could do with an extra pillow

329
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:39,640
and I'm very disappointed
with your breakfast bar

330
00:16:39,720 --> 00:16:42,480
and all of the dying.

331
00:16:45,840 --> 00:16:49,000
This is not exactly
within your job description.

332
00:16:50,040 --> 00:16:52,960
Come on, Captain. Where would we be
if we all followed our job descriptions,

333
00:16:53,040 --> 00:16:54,760
hmm? Good question. Glad you asked.

334
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:57,400
In your case, you'd be doing something

335
00:16:57,760 --> 00:16:58,840
instead of climbing inside a bottle.

336
00:16:59,080 --> 00:17:01,960
I have followed the procedure
for accidental death to the letter.

337
00:17:02,160 --> 00:17:03,160
Yes, I'm sure you have.

338
00:17:03,240 --> 00:17:05,760
And I'm sure you do just enough
of your job to avoid complaints.

339
00:17:05,840 --> 00:17:07,440
You don't know anything about me.

340
00:17:07,520 --> 00:17:10,280
Wounded in battle, honourable discharge.

341
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:14,120
And this is just a guess, but I think
you've had the fight knocked out of you.

342
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:16,280
You expected this to be a cushy desk job

343
00:17:16,360 --> 00:17:18,000
where you could put your head down
until retirement.

344
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:19,440
Well, I'm sorry.

345
00:17:19,800 --> 00:17:21,480
As of today, that dream is over.

346
00:17:21,560 --> 00:17:23,840
There is no evidence of any attack
or other parties...

347
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,040
Yes, let's just sit around
and wait for the evidence

348
00:17:26,120 --> 00:17:27,400
while the bodies pile up.

349
00:17:27,520 --> 00:17:28,920
Or here's a crazy thought,

350
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:31,800
we could do something to stop it.

351
00:17:35,920 --> 00:17:37,680
Why am I even talking to you?

352
00:17:40,480 --> 00:17:43,240
Uh, passenger manifest,
plan of the train

353
00:17:43,320 --> 00:17:45,920
and a list of stops
for the past six months.

354
00:17:46,200 --> 00:17:47,680
Quick work, Perkins.

355
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:50,560
Maybe too quick.

356
00:17:51,080 --> 00:17:52,360
Yes, sir.

357
00:17:52,480 --> 00:17:54,240
I'm obviously the mummy.

358
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:57,960
Or perhaps
I was already looking into this.

359
00:18:00,840 --> 00:18:02,320
This Doctor,

360
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:04,880
he's your what, exactly?

361
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:07,280
Hmm. He's not my anything.

362
00:18:08,280 --> 00:18:10,200
Oh, you mean you're just friends.

363
00:18:10,560 --> 00:18:12,440
(CHUCKLES) Yeah, of course
we're just friends.

364
00:18:12,840 --> 00:18:13,840
Well,

365
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:15,760
we're not even friends, not any more.

366
00:18:15,960 --> 00:18:17,200
Well, that clearly isn't true.

367
00:18:17,280 --> 00:18:19,800
No, it's true. It is. It's very true.

368
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:23,280
-You do seem to be here together.
-Seriously?

369
00:18:23,360 --> 00:18:25,080
We're stuck in this carriage,
probably all night,

370
00:18:25,160 --> 00:18:26,480
and all we can talk about is some man?

371
00:18:26,560 --> 00:18:27,760
Some man?

372
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:29,240
Not that kind of...

373
00:18:31,680 --> 00:18:32,680
(SIGHS)

374
00:18:33,080 --> 00:18:34,800
Look, we, um...

375
00:18:35,600 --> 00:18:38,760
We knocked about together,
we travelled and now we're stopping.

376
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:40,560
This is a...

377
00:18:42,200 --> 00:18:45,400
I don't know, goodbye to the good times.

378
00:18:49,280 --> 00:18:51,040
Were the good times all like this?

379
00:18:51,120 --> 00:18:52,400
(CHUCKLES) Yeah.

380
00:18:53,160 --> 00:18:54,360
Now that you mention it.

381
00:18:54,440 --> 00:18:58,720
-No! No! Get it out! (SCREAMS)
-(CLOCK TICKING)

382
00:19:00,840 --> 00:19:03,280
66 seconds. It fits the myth.

383
00:19:03,880 --> 00:19:05,280
-Did you see the lights flicker?
-Mmm.

384
00:19:05,360 --> 00:19:08,480
Yeah, the lights went in the kitchen
as well, just before the chef saw it.

385
00:19:08,560 --> 00:19:09,560
In all of the accounts,

386
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:11,840
conventional weapons have no effect
on the Foretold.

387
00:19:12,240 --> 00:19:14,440
It's immortal, unstoppable.

388
00:19:15,400 --> 00:19:16,600
Unkillable.

389
00:19:16,720 --> 00:19:18,400
Can we get a new expert?

390
00:19:23,840 --> 00:19:25,920
-Oh, he was wrong.
-Yes. Yes. Yes, he was.

391
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:29,680
(STAMMERING)
And high-handed and thoughtless

392
00:19:29,760 --> 00:19:31,320
and arrogant beyond belief.

393
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:32,400
Exactly.

394
00:19:32,480 --> 00:19:34,160
And you got on a train with him.

395
00:19:35,080 --> 00:19:36,600
I was saying goodbye.

396
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:39,080
You can't end it on a slammed door.

397
00:19:39,160 --> 00:19:40,880
Yes, you can. Anyone can do it.

398
00:19:41,120 --> 00:19:42,720
People do it all the time.

399
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:45,560
Except, of course, when they can't.

400
00:19:46,960 --> 00:19:47,960
(MAISIE SIGHS)

401
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:51,520
Life would be so much simpler
if you liked the right people,

402
00:19:52,160 --> 00:19:54,000
people you're supposed to like.

403
00:19:55,600 --> 00:19:57,840
But then I guess there'd be
no fairy tales.

404
00:20:07,360 --> 00:20:08,920
(ALARM BEEPING)

405
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:15,320
(SNORING)

406
00:20:18,200 --> 00:20:19,600
(WHIRRING)

407
00:20:23,640 --> 00:20:25,040
(MOBILE RINGING)

408
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:27,680
-Doctor?
-Wake up, sleepyhead,

409
00:20:27,760 --> 00:20:30,040
time for breakfast.
Knowing this train, it'll taste amazing.

410
00:20:30,120 --> 00:20:32,320
-Doctor, please, I'm in trouble.
-Can't even get that right, huh?

411
00:20:32,400 --> 00:20:33,960
-Doctor...
-Bad food on trains is traditional.

412
00:20:34,040 --> 00:20:35,200
-Doctor, please, just...
-Listen.

413
00:20:35,320 --> 00:20:37,280
There's been another mummy murder.

414
00:20:37,360 --> 00:20:39,560
So our last hurrah just became
a bit more interesting.

415
00:20:39,640 --> 00:20:41,720
-I'm trapped!
-What?

416
00:20:42,440 --> 00:20:43,640
Where are you?

417
00:20:48,800 --> 00:20:49,960
Clara!

418
00:20:50,960 --> 00:20:53,720
-Is that you?
-Yes. Yes. Hello. Uh, can you hear us?

419
00:20:53,960 --> 00:20:55,040
Ooh!

420
00:20:57,920 --> 00:20:59,760
Computer, can you open the door, please?

421
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:00,840
GUS: Gall me Gus.

422
00:21:00,920 --> 00:21:04,520
I'm afraid this door can only be opened
by executive order.

423
00:21:04,640 --> 00:21:05,760
Oh, forget it.

424
00:21:06,520 --> 00:21:07,680
(WHIRRING)

425
00:21:11,080 --> 00:21:13,600
Now the stupid sonic screwdriver's
not working.

426
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:15,000
What do you mean it's not working? Why?

427
00:21:15,080 --> 00:21:18,320
I don't know. Some sort of
suppression field, I would guess.

428
00:21:18,400 --> 00:21:20,040
And it has to be a guess
because, as I say,

429
00:21:20,120 --> 00:21:22,280
the stupid sonic screwdriver's
not working.

430
00:21:22,360 --> 00:21:23,560
What are you even doing in there?

431
00:21:23,640 --> 00:21:26,240
Well, I was looking for you,
Mr Nothing To Worry About.

432
00:21:26,320 --> 00:21:28,680
What, was I supposed to waken you up?

433
00:21:28,840 --> 00:21:30,800
Drag you out of bed
because I had a hunch?

434
00:21:30,880 --> 00:21:32,320
I thought you didn't want
to do this any more.

435
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:34,600
Look, please,
can we just not do this now?

436
00:21:34,680 --> 00:21:36,960
I think we might not be alone in here.

437
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:39,040
There's a sarcophagus.

438
00:21:39,160 --> 00:21:40,160
Is it in there?

439
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:42,280
(BEEPS)

440
00:21:42,960 --> 00:21:45,760
I think we might
just be about to find out.

441
00:21:46,240 --> 00:21:49,960
Turns out the sonic is working,
just not on the door we need.

442
00:21:57,800 --> 00:21:59,680
Clara, it's coming.

443
00:22:06,520 --> 00:22:07,520
Doctor?

444
00:22:09,680 --> 00:22:11,000
(SIGHS IN RELIEF)

445
00:22:11,080 --> 00:22:15,280
Doctor, it's okay.
It's full of bubble wrap.

446
00:22:17,040 --> 00:22:19,760
-Did the lights...
-Doctor, move away from the door.

447
00:22:19,840 --> 00:22:22,160
-My friend's inside.
-Then they're in trouble, too.

448
00:22:22,320 --> 00:22:23,440
I spoke to head office.

449
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:25,200
There is no mystery shopper.

450
00:22:25,360 --> 00:22:26,840
You're not even on the passenger list.

451
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:29,000
Clara, I'm going to have
to call you back.

452
00:22:29,840 --> 00:22:31,560
You know, I'm going to have to
mark you down for this.

453
00:22:31,640 --> 00:22:33,960
You are not a mystery shopper.

454
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:36,360
For all I know,
you're the one behind the killings.

455
00:22:36,720 --> 00:22:38,200
DOCTOR: Oh, come on, Captain.

456
00:22:38,360 --> 00:22:40,880
How many people have to die
before you stop looking the other way?

457
00:22:40,960 --> 00:22:42,520
-(GUNSHOT)
-Get back!

458
00:22:42,840 --> 00:22:43,960
(GUNSHOT)

459
00:22:44,720 --> 00:22:45,760
Stay back!

460
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:50,560
What do you think you're doing, man?

461
00:22:51,680 --> 00:22:52,680
Please stop! No!

462
00:22:53,040 --> 00:22:54,640
Get up now! That's an order!

463
00:22:54,720 --> 00:22:56,520
(SOBBING) Don't, please, don't...

464
00:23:08,680 --> 00:23:10,360
It turns out it's three.

465
00:23:11,640 --> 00:23:14,920
The amount of people that had to die
before I stopped looking the other way.

466
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:16,000
Thank you.

467
00:23:17,360 --> 00:23:19,240
Same as the others.

468
00:23:27,720 --> 00:23:31,160
Ladies and gentlemen, could I have
a moment of your time, please?

469
00:23:33,360 --> 00:23:35,080
There's a monster on this train

470
00:23:36,160 --> 00:23:38,840
that can only be seen
by those about to die.

471
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:42,640
If you do see it,
you will have exactly 66 seconds left

472
00:23:42,720 --> 00:23:45,640
in which to live.
But that isn't even the strangest thing.

473
00:23:47,440 --> 00:23:48,720
Do you know what is?

474
00:23:49,520 --> 00:23:50,600
You.

475
00:23:52,160 --> 00:23:53,160
The passengers.

476
00:23:53,840 --> 00:23:59,080
Experts in alien biology,
mythology, physics.

477
00:23:59,600 --> 00:24:02,440
If I was putting together a team
to analyse this thing,

478
00:24:02,520 --> 00:24:03,720
I'd pick you.

479
00:24:05,720 --> 00:24:07,560
And I think somebody has.

480
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:10,400
Someone of immense power and influence

481
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:13,000
has orchestrated this whole trip.

482
00:24:13,600 --> 00:24:18,040
Someone who I have no doubt
is listening to us right now.

483
00:24:20,280 --> 00:24:23,120
So, are you going to step out
from behind the curtain

484
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:24,960
and give us our orders?

485
00:24:25,600 --> 00:24:27,840
The engines. They've stopped.

486
00:24:40,280 --> 00:24:42,520
And the facade drops away

487
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:45,480
because what use are
a bunch of scientists without a lab?

488
00:24:49,040 --> 00:24:50,400
Teleporter?

489
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:52,800
No.

490
00:24:52,880 --> 00:24:54,480
Hard light holograms.

491
00:24:54,760 --> 00:24:56,040
They were never really here.

492
00:24:56,200 --> 00:24:58,200
Fake passengers to make up the numbers.

493
00:24:58,360 --> 00:25:00,000
That was my best guard.

494
00:25:00,120 --> 00:25:02,000
-(BELL DINGS)
-GUS: Good morning, everyone.

495
00:25:02,120 --> 00:25:05,880
Around the room, you will find
a variety of scientific equipment.

496
00:25:06,120 --> 00:25:09,480
Your goal is to ascertain
the Foretold"s true nature,

497
00:25:09,560 --> 00:25:12,280
probe for weaknesses
with a view to capture,

498
00:25:12,360 --> 00:25:15,520
after which we will reverse engineer
its abilities.

499
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:17,240
Isn't this exciting?

500
00:25:17,320 --> 00:25:20,480
You said "capture”, implying that
you can't control this thing.

501
00:25:20,560 --> 00:25:22,840
And yet somehow you got it
on board. How?

502
00:25:22,920 --> 00:25:25,800
There is an artefact an ancient scroll.

503
00:25:25,920 --> 00:25:28,240
I have highlighted it
for your convenience.

504
00:25:29,040 --> 00:25:30,960
For reasons currently unknown,

505
00:25:31,040 --> 00:25:34,520
the Foretold appears in the vicinity
of this artefact.

506
00:25:34,680 --> 00:25:36,320
And kills at regular intervals.

507
00:25:36,520 --> 00:25:39,080
Then just maybe we should just
throw this thing out in the airlock.

508
00:25:39,160 --> 00:25:40,880
-No! No! No!
- (ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

509
00:25:43,920 --> 00:25:45,240
Looks like they've thought of that.

510
00:25:45,320 --> 00:25:46,600
MOORHOUSE: What if we say no?

511
00:25:47,360 --> 00:25:48,360
Down tools.

512
00:25:49,040 --> 00:25:50,240
Refuse to work.

513
00:25:50,480 --> 00:25:52,280
That is your choice, of course.

514
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:55,400
But it would be very upsetting
were you all to die

515
00:25:55,480 --> 00:25:57,000
at the hands of the Foretold.

516
00:25:57,520 --> 00:25:59,760
So hurry up before it kills you.

517
00:25:59,840 --> 00:26:00,920
But even if they agree to this,

518
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:03,280
how are they supposed to study
a creature they can't even see?

519
00:26:03,360 --> 00:26:04,920
We don't even know what the species is.

520
00:26:05,360 --> 00:26:06,920
DOCTOR: Perkins, start the clock.

521
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:09,160
Approximately 1.8 metres tall.

522
00:26:09,800 --> 00:26:11,880
Actually, seeing it in the flesh

523
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:14,520
isn't nearly as rewarding
as I thought it might be.

524
00:26:14,600 --> 00:26:16,240
Oh, dear. Hard cheese.
What can you see? Details.

525
00:26:16,320 --> 00:26:19,200
Yes. Yes, of course. Of course.
Well, it just looks like, um,

526
00:26:19,280 --> 00:26:21,200
a man in bandages. I...

527
00:26:21,320 --> 00:26:23,000
-What kind of bandages? Old? New?
-Old.

528
00:26:23,080 --> 00:26:24,920
-Whole? Ragged?
-Ragged. Falling off in places.

529
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:26,160
I don't know what you
want me to tell you!

530
00:26:26,240 --> 00:26:28,240
Listen to me! You can see this thing.
We can't.

531
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:29,320
Tell us what you can see.

532
00:26:29,400 --> 00:26:32,440
Even the smallest detail
might help us save the next one.

533
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:33,640
The next one?

534
00:26:33,880 --> 00:26:35,880
You mean, you can't save me?

535
00:26:35,960 --> 00:26:37,160
Well, that is implied, isn't it?

536
00:26:37,240 --> 00:26:39,280
Yes, this is probably the end for you.

537
00:26:39,360 --> 00:26:41,640
But make it count! Details, please!

538
00:26:41,720 --> 00:26:44,360
-Um, flesh, some of it is visible...
-30 seconds.

539
00:26:44,440 --> 00:26:46,640
Leathery. Ancient-looking.
Peat-bog preserved.

540
00:26:46,720 --> 00:26:48,200
Keep talking! Don't waste this chance!

541
00:26:48,280 --> 00:26:50,640
-I want to bargain for my life.
-(STAMMERING) What?

542
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:52,880
In some of the myths it says
if you find the right word,

543
00:26:52,960 --> 00:26:54,280
make the right offer,
then it lets you go.

544
00:26:54,360 --> 00:26:57,120
This is not a myth. This is real.
Forget your superstitions.

545
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:58,240
Tell us what you can see!

546
00:26:58,320 --> 00:27:00,080
This is my life! My death!

547
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:01,600
I'm going to fight for it how I want!

548
00:27:01,680 --> 00:27:04,440
-1... I give you my soul.
-Ten seconds.

549
00:27:04,520 --> 00:27:07,040
I confess all my sins.
I give you all my worldly goods.

550
00:27:07,120 --> 00:27:09,640
Only, please, please, please. No!

551
00:27:14,960 --> 00:27:16,120
Zero.

552
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:18,320
-(BELL DINGS)
-GUS: We apologise for any distress

553
00:27:18,400 --> 00:27:20,040
you may have just experienced.

554
00:27:20,320 --> 00:27:22,800
Grief counselling is available
on request.

555
00:27:23,120 --> 00:27:26,800
On the bright side, I'm sure
you've all collected a lot of data.

556
00:27:26,960 --> 00:27:28,000
Well done, everyone!

557
00:27:28,080 --> 00:27:29,280
It's recording every death.

558
00:27:29,360 --> 00:27:30,480
Of course it is.

559
00:27:30,800 --> 00:27:32,040
That's why we're here.

560
00:27:32,120 --> 00:27:34,120
To study our own demise.

561
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:37,800
So let's get to work.
Come on. Chop, chop.

562
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:42,760
(MOBILE RINGING)

563
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:47,600
Clara Oswald.

564
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:49,680
Okay. So first things first,

565
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:53,200
the sarcophagus is actually
a secure stasis unit.

566
00:27:53,280 --> 00:27:56,240
Yes. It's where they want us
to put the Foretold if we capture it.

567
00:27:56,320 --> 00:27:57,440
Well, that would have been good to know.

568
00:27:57,560 --> 00:27:59,920
Sorry. Teeny bit busy round here.
What else?

569
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:02,080
-(BELL DINGS)
-GUS: Please terminate your call

570
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:03,520
and return to work.

571
00:28:03,600 --> 00:28:04,760
CLARA: I have some paperwork.

572
00:28:04,840 --> 00:28:06,360
Passenger manifests from other ships.

573
00:28:06,440 --> 00:28:07,760
Maisie recognised a couple of the names.

574
00:28:07,840 --> 00:28:09,600
These are missing ships.

575
00:28:09,840 --> 00:28:11,720
-DOCTOR: So we're not the first.
-No.

576
00:28:12,680 --> 00:28:16,480
GUS: Please terminate your call
and return to work.

577
00:28:16,960 --> 00:28:19,520
I've got some progress reports.
The Gloriana

578
00:28:19,720 --> 00:28:21,880
spent three days
getting picked off by the Foretold.

579
00:28:21,960 --> 00:28:24,120
All died. Performance marked as "poor".

580
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:27,440
GUS: Warning,
decompression imminent.

581
00:28:27,520 --> 00:28:29,240
Please vacate the area.

582
00:28:29,400 --> 00:28:30,400
Ah!

583
00:28:31,920 --> 00:28:33,400
The Valiant Heart.

584
00:28:36,320 --> 00:28:39,280
Forty-two crew, four died.
Performance "promising".

585
00:28:39,560 --> 00:28:42,800
GUS: Please terminate the call
and return to work.

586
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:50,640
I think you should do as it says.

587
00:28:53,440 --> 00:28:54,600
(WOMAN GASPING)

588
00:28:59,080 --> 00:29:00,360
Clara, I have to go.

589
00:29:02,200 --> 00:29:05,360
GUS: I'm sorry. I know that must
have been distressing for you.

590
00:29:05,680 --> 00:29:08,000
But if you are disobedient again,

591
00:29:08,080 --> 00:29:10,400
I will decompress another area

592
00:29:10,480 --> 00:29:12,720
containing less valuable passengers.

593
00:29:13,840 --> 00:29:15,680
Less valuable passengers?

594
00:29:16,840 --> 00:29:18,040
How does it choose?

595
00:29:19,120 --> 00:29:21,360
Well, I'm assuming qualifications...

596
00:29:21,440 --> 00:29:24,640
No, no, no.
Not the computer, the Foretold.

597
00:29:25,880 --> 00:29:27,520
How does it choose who to kill?

598
00:29:28,320 --> 00:29:30,440
We've assumed it's random.
What if it's not?

599
00:29:31,160 --> 00:29:33,400
I want full histories
on all the victims.

600
00:29:33,480 --> 00:29:35,680
Medical, social, personal.

601
00:29:36,200 --> 00:29:37,640
GUS: Well done.

602
00:29:38,160 --> 00:29:39,400
Don't mention it.

603
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:46,880
Doesn't seem to be any pattern.

604
00:29:46,960 --> 00:29:49,960
Their travel history,
interests, health...

605
00:29:50,040 --> 00:29:51,120
It's all over the shop.

606
00:29:51,200 --> 00:29:52,520
Health? Are you sure?

607
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:55,760
Mrs Pitt, the first victim.
She was over 100 years old,

608
00:29:56,160 --> 00:29:57,520
the frailest passenger on board.

609
00:29:57,600 --> 00:30:01,520
But the next to go, the chef,
was young and fit. It's random.

610
00:30:01,600 --> 00:30:03,400
The chef was ill.

611
00:30:04,640 --> 00:30:05,760
What?

612
00:30:06,280 --> 00:30:07,920
A rare blood disorder.

613
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:09,840
Not contagious but we kept it quiet.

614
00:30:09,920 --> 00:30:11,040
Because he worked with food.

615
00:30:11,120 --> 00:30:12,280
The next one, the guard?

616
00:30:12,360 --> 00:30:13,400
He wasn't ill, as such

617
00:30:13,560 --> 00:30:16,400
but he did have synthetic lungs
implanted last year.

618
00:30:16,480 --> 00:30:17,960
Professor Moorhouse.

619
00:30:18,040 --> 00:30:21,040
It seems he was physically fine
but suffering from...

620
00:30:21,320 --> 00:30:25,280
Here we are. Regular panic attacks
after a car crash last year.

621
00:30:25,400 --> 00:30:27,040
It's picking off the weakest first.

622
00:30:27,480 --> 00:30:29,320
Sensing the illness somehow.

623
00:30:29,640 --> 00:30:32,160
The fake organs,
even psychological issues.

624
00:30:32,240 --> 00:30:33,280
But this is good news

625
00:30:33,360 --> 00:30:35,840
because it means we can work out
who is next.

626
00:30:35,920 --> 00:30:38,640
I want the medical records
of everybody alive

627
00:30:38,720 --> 00:30:40,080
who is still on board.

628
00:30:40,240 --> 00:30:42,680
If anyone's had as much as a cold,
I want to know about it.

629
00:30:42,960 --> 00:30:46,280
You really think it can sense
psychological issues?

630
00:30:46,360 --> 00:30:47,640
It seems so. Why?

631
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:51,840
When you said I'd lost the stomach
for a fight,

632
00:30:51,920 --> 00:30:56,280
I wasn't wounded in battle, as such
but my unit was bombed.

633
00:30:57,440 --> 00:30:58,760
I was the sole survivor.

634
00:30:59,200 --> 00:31:00,640
Not a scratch on me.

635
00:31:01,920 --> 00:31:03,680
But post-traumatic stress...

636
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:06,320
Nightmares.

637
00:31:08,880 --> 00:31:10,680
I still can't sleep without pills.

638
00:31:12,560 --> 00:31:15,320
Which means that you are probably next.

639
00:31:16,280 --> 00:31:18,720
-Which is good to know.
-Well, not for me.

640
00:31:18,800 --> 00:31:20,720
Well, of course, not for you
because you're going to die.

641
00:31:20,800 --> 00:31:23,040
But I mean, for us,
from a research point of view.

642
00:31:23,120 --> 00:31:25,200
You know, for a doctor,
your bedside manner...

643
00:31:29,040 --> 00:31:31,680
Well, there's goes our head start.
Perkins, start the clock.

644
00:31:33,360 --> 00:31:34,400
What can you see?

645
00:31:34,480 --> 00:31:35,880
Almost feels

646
00:31:36,440 --> 00:31:38,000
out of focus.

647
00:31:39,080 --> 00:31:40,400
Gives me a headache just looking at it.

648
00:31:40,480 --> 00:31:42,480
Oh, no, no, no. That didn't work before.

649
00:31:42,560 --> 00:31:45,040
What kind of soldier would I be
dying with bullets in my gun?

650
00:31:45,120 --> 00:31:46,680
-(GUNSHOTS)
-(GLASS SHATTERING)

651
00:31:48,680 --> 00:31:51,440
-Fifty seconds.
-Someone shut that man up!

652
00:31:52,800 --> 00:31:55,120
For the record, it didn't even flinch.

653
00:31:55,200 --> 00:31:56,200
Where is it now?

654
00:31:56,280 --> 00:31:58,840
Approximately 20 feet in front of me
and closing.

655
00:31:58,920 --> 00:32:01,360
-Forty seconds.
-Am I close?

656
00:32:02,640 --> 00:32:05,320
It's passing right through you,
like a ghost.

657
00:32:05,480 --> 00:32:06,480
It's not a hologram.

658
00:32:06,560 --> 00:32:07,720
If you move, will it follow?

659
00:32:07,800 --> 00:32:10,320
Do you want me to move?
Because I can certainly do that.

660
00:32:10,400 --> 00:32:12,520
Keep looking at it.
But back off quick as you like.

661
00:32:12,600 --> 00:32:13,840
It's teleported away.

662
00:32:16,160 --> 00:32:17,360
It's behind me.

663
00:32:18,720 --> 00:32:21,520
-Twenty seconds.
-I think this is it.

664
00:32:21,800 --> 00:32:24,160
Still, suppose it's not a bad way to go.

665
00:32:24,240 --> 00:32:25,400
Blood pumping,

666
00:32:25,600 --> 00:32:27,280
enemy at the gates and all that.

667
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:29,400
And thank you, Doctor,

668
00:32:29,800 --> 00:32:31,120
for waking me up.

669
00:32:32,480 --> 00:32:33,680
It's reaching for me.

670
00:32:33,880 --> 00:32:35,800
Hands on my head.

671
00:32:38,640 --> 00:32:39,640
Zero.

672
00:32:39,720 --> 00:32:40,720
(GROANS)

673
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:44,200
Teleporter, that means tech.

674
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:46,120
Then 66 seconds, to do what?

675
00:32:46,200 --> 00:32:48,040
66 seconds.
That seems very, very specific.

676
00:32:48,120 --> 00:32:50,520
Too specific for organic.
So, what? More tech?

677
00:32:50,720 --> 00:32:52,680
What? More?
A countdown clock? Something charging?

678
00:32:52,760 --> 00:32:55,920
A man just died in front of us.
Can we not just have a moment?

679
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:58,800
Oh, no, no, no.
We can't do that. We can't mourn.

680
00:32:58,880 --> 00:33:01,240
People with guns to their heads,
they cannot mourn.

681
00:33:01,320 --> 00:33:02,880
We do not have time to mourn.

682
00:33:03,120 --> 00:33:06,560
Everybody, what takes 66 seconds
to charge up

683
00:33:06,640 --> 00:33:09,640
or to change state? Anyone?

684
00:33:10,920 --> 00:33:11,960
(SIGHS)

685
00:33:12,040 --> 00:33:13,480
Am I surrounded by idiots?

686
00:33:14,040 --> 00:33:15,400
If only I could see this thing!

687
00:33:15,480 --> 00:33:16,880
Don't even joke about that.

688
00:33:16,960 --> 00:33:18,040
I'm not joking about it.

689
00:33:18,120 --> 00:33:20,880
One minute with me and this thing,
it would be over!

690
00:33:21,680 --> 00:33:24,560
You know, Doctor,
I can't tell if you're a genius

691
00:33:24,640 --> 00:33:26,600
or just incredibly arrogant.

692
00:33:26,680 --> 00:33:28,920
Well, on a good day, I'm both.

693
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:31,720
Ancient tech.

694
00:33:31,800 --> 00:33:35,440
This thing has been around
for centuries. How?

695
00:33:36,360 --> 00:33:39,200
Tech that keeps it alive.

696
00:33:39,280 --> 00:33:42,440
Tech that drains energy
from the living.

697
00:33:42,520 --> 00:33:43,760
(CLAPS) Scanner!

698
00:33:45,200 --> 00:33:46,200
(WHIRRING)

699
00:33:48,720 --> 00:33:50,360
Deep tissue scan.

700
00:33:51,800 --> 00:33:55,920
He's been leached of almost
all energy on a cellular level.

701
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:58,280
The heart attack is just a...
is just a side effect.

702
00:33:58,400 --> 00:34:00,880
Oh, it's not just a mummy,
it's a vampire.

703
00:34:01,760 --> 00:34:03,160
Metaphorically speaking.

704
00:34:03,240 --> 00:34:05,280
But why take 66 seconds to drain us?

705
00:34:05,360 --> 00:34:06,560
Why not just pounce?

706
00:34:06,640 --> 00:34:09,600
Phase. Moving energy out of phase.

707
00:34:09,680 --> 00:34:11,280
That takes about a minute, doesn't it?

708
00:34:11,360 --> 00:34:14,000
That's why only the victims can see it.

709
00:34:14,520 --> 00:34:17,480
It takes them out of phase
so it can drain their energy.

710
00:34:17,600 --> 00:34:21,320
You, sir, are a genius!
This explains everything.

711
00:34:21,960 --> 00:34:23,560
Apart from what it is
and how it's doing it.

712
00:34:23,640 --> 00:34:24,680
Sorry, I jumped the gun there

713
00:34:24,760 --> 00:34:26,720
with the "you're a genius,
that explains everything” remark.

714
00:34:26,840 --> 00:34:28,160
Doctor,

715
00:34:28,240 --> 00:34:30,280
I think we know the next victim.

716
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:33,560
Ah, of course.

717
00:34:34,320 --> 00:34:36,680
That makes perfect sense.

718
00:34:39,200 --> 00:34:41,080
Look, she's had a bad day, that's all.

719
00:34:41,160 --> 00:34:42,400
DOCTOR: Clara, it doesn't care.

720
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:44,480
Her bad day, her bereavement,

721
00:34:44,560 --> 00:34:47,640
her little breakdown puts her
squarely in its crosshairs.

722
00:34:48,480 --> 00:34:49,560
She's next.

723
00:34:49,720 --> 00:34:51,360
Every simulation we've run confirms it.

724
00:34:51,440 --> 00:34:55,360
Okay, but... But we're in here and
if we stay in here, that thing can't...

725
00:34:55,480 --> 00:34:56,640
DOCTOR: This thing can teleport.

726
00:34:56,720 --> 00:34:59,280
We need her here.
Even the computer agrees.

727
00:34:59,440 --> 00:35:02,320
Okay, so you can save her? Right?

728
00:35:02,520 --> 00:35:04,480
Of course not. Why would you think that?

729
00:35:04,800 --> 00:35:07,080
This is another chance
to observe it in action.

730
00:35:07,160 --> 00:35:08,320
As it kills her.

731
00:35:08,400 --> 00:35:10,600
Of course as it kills her.

732
00:35:10,680 --> 00:35:12,120
If it happens in there,
it'll be a waste

733
00:35:12,200 --> 00:35:14,200
so bring her to us.

734
00:35:14,320 --> 00:35:15,320
How?

735
00:35:15,440 --> 00:35:17,680
How, exactly?
She's never going to agree to this.

736
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:19,160
Well, I don't know. Lie to her.

737
00:35:19,240 --> 00:35:22,640
Tell her I can save her.
Whatever it takes to get her here.

738
00:35:26,320 --> 00:35:27,560
What's he saying?

739
00:35:30,040 --> 00:35:31,360
He says...

740
00:35:38,280 --> 00:35:39,800
He says he can save you.

741
00:35:41,440 --> 00:35:43,440
I knew he could get us out of there!

742
00:35:43,520 --> 00:35:45,720
I told you, he's a good man.

743
00:35:46,520 --> 00:35:49,160
Yes. Yes, he is.

744
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:51,160
And to be honest, I don't know
how convinced I am

745
00:35:51,240 --> 00:35:53,040
by this "trauma sense" thing,

746
00:35:53,120 --> 00:35:55,040
but if the Doctor says
he can help me anyway...

747
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:57,760
I mean, that has to be a good thing,
doesn't it, Clara?

748
00:36:09,680 --> 00:36:11,240
Hello again. I'm Maisie.

749
00:36:11,320 --> 00:36:12,640
-Good for you.
-Huh?

750
00:36:13,240 --> 00:36:15,040
We passed the Tardis on the way here.

751
00:36:15,120 --> 00:36:16,360
Thought about getting inside,

752
00:36:16,560 --> 00:36:19,040
hiding, pulling the levers
and hoping for the best.

753
00:36:19,120 --> 00:36:20,440
But we couldn't even get in.

754
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:22,160
There was a force field around it.

755
00:36:22,880 --> 00:36:25,120
It's probably Gus trying to block
our escape route.

756
00:36:25,200 --> 00:36:26,200
But how does he even know what it is?

757
00:36:26,280 --> 00:36:28,480
'Cause if he knows what it is,
then he knows what you are.

758
00:36:30,840 --> 00:36:34,440
Well, he has tried
to entice me here before.

759
00:36:34,720 --> 00:36:38,120
Free tickets, mysterious summons,
he even phoned the Tardis one night.

760
00:36:38,200 --> 00:36:39,840
-Do you know how difficult...
-You knew.

761
00:36:39,920 --> 00:36:42,040
You knew this was no relaxing break.

762
00:36:42,120 --> 00:36:43,760
You knew this was dangerous.

763
00:36:43,840 --> 00:36:46,480
I didn't know. I certainly hoped.

764
00:36:46,560 --> 00:36:49,520
Okay, this. You see, this.
This is why I'm leaving you. This.

765
00:36:49,600 --> 00:36:51,280
Because you lied. You lied to me again.

766
00:36:51,360 --> 00:36:54,560
And now you've made me lie.
You've made me your accomplice.

767
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:55,960
What? Sorry?

768
00:36:56,040 --> 00:36:59,400
When did you lie? Clara?

769
00:37:00,680 --> 00:37:03,280
Maisie, I am... I am so sorry.

770
00:37:06,120 --> 00:37:07,120
(GASPS)

771
00:37:10,040 --> 00:37:11,280
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

772
00:37:14,600 --> 00:37:16,400
-Do we start the clock?
-Not yet.

773
00:37:17,480 --> 00:37:19,200
Focus. Focus. Focus!

774
00:37:19,920 --> 00:37:22,400
All of that is your grief,

775
00:37:22,920 --> 00:37:24,320
your trauma,

776
00:37:24,600 --> 00:37:25,880
your resentment.

777
00:37:25,960 --> 00:37:28,760
And now it's mine.

778
00:37:31,160 --> 00:37:32,280
It's gone!

779
00:37:32,360 --> 00:37:34,400
No. No, it's not. Not for me.

780
00:37:34,480 --> 00:37:36,400
Because now it thinks I'm you.

781
00:37:38,320 --> 00:37:39,480
Start the clock.

782
00:37:42,520 --> 00:37:43,680
Hello.

783
00:37:46,120 --> 00:37:48,160
I'm so pleased to finally see you.

784
00:37:48,520 --> 00:37:50,320
I'm the Doctor
and I will be your victim this evening.

785
00:37:50,400 --> 00:37:51,560
Are you my mummy?

786
00:37:53,160 --> 00:37:56,040
But you can't hurt me
until my time is up. I think.

787
00:37:56,120 --> 00:37:57,400
So are there magic words?

788
00:37:57,480 --> 00:37:59,800
Is there a way
to stop you in your tracks?

789
00:38:00,040 --> 00:38:02,240
Oh, you really didn't like your gran,
did you?

790
00:38:03,640 --> 00:38:05,720
There's something visible
under the bandages.

791
00:38:05,960 --> 00:38:07,560
By the way, you weren't being paranoid.

792
00:38:07,640 --> 00:38:09,240
She really did poison your pony.

793
00:38:09,320 --> 00:38:10,320
Oh!

794
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:11,960
Markings like the ones on the scroll.

795
00:38:12,040 --> 00:38:14,120
-Oh, and your father. Sorry.
-What?

796
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:17,000
A tattered piece of cloth attached to
a length of wood that you will kill for.

797
00:38:17,080 --> 00:38:18,360
-Thirty seconds.
-That doesn't sound like a scroll.

798
00:38:18,440 --> 00:38:20,920
That sounds like... A flag!

799
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:22,280
And if that sounds like a flag,

800
00:38:22,360 --> 00:38:23,880
if this is a flag, that means that you

801
00:38:23,960 --> 00:38:25,200
are a soldier!

802
00:38:26,360 --> 00:38:30,040
Wounded in a forgotten war
thousands of years ago.

803
00:38:30,200 --> 00:38:32,080
But they've worked on you,
haven't they, son?

804
00:38:32,160 --> 00:38:33,640
(WHISPERING)
They've filled you full of kit.

805
00:38:33,720 --> 00:38:36,560
State-of-the-art phase camouflage,
personal teleporter.

806
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:37,720
Ten seconds.

807
00:38:37,800 --> 00:38:41,400
And all that tech inside you,
it just won't let you die, will it?

808
00:38:41,480 --> 00:38:42,680
It won't let the war end.

809
00:38:42,760 --> 00:38:45,520
It just won't let you stop
until the war is over.

810
00:38:45,640 --> 00:38:47,160
We surrender!

811
00:38:47,240 --> 00:38:48,320
Zero.

812
00:38:48,520 --> 00:38:50,280
(GASPS) I can see it again.

813
00:38:51,480 --> 00:38:54,640
It's okay. I think we all can.

814
00:38:55,960 --> 00:38:58,160
-Do I start the clock?
-No.

815
00:39:00,040 --> 00:39:01,040
(MOANING)

816
00:39:02,320 --> 00:39:03,760
The clock has stopped.

817
00:39:07,440 --> 00:39:09,120
You're relieved, soldier.

818
00:39:13,200 --> 00:39:14,360
He's not the only one.

819
00:39:15,800 --> 00:39:18,160
-CLARA: We were fighting that?
-So was he.

820
00:39:19,480 --> 00:39:20,480
Listen, what I said...

821
00:39:20,560 --> 00:39:22,600
Save it. We're not out of the woods yet.

822
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:25,960
Well, Gus, I think we solved
your little puzzle.

823
00:39:26,640 --> 00:39:30,560
Ancient soldier being driven
by malfunctioning tech.

824
00:39:30,920 --> 00:39:32,920
GUS: Thank you so much
for your efforts.

825
00:39:33,200 --> 00:39:35,040
They are greatly appreciated.

826
00:39:35,480 --> 00:39:39,400
Unfortunately, survivors
of this exercise are not required.

827
00:39:39,480 --> 00:39:41,000
Ah, well, there's a shocker.

828
00:39:41,320 --> 00:39:44,240
Air will now be removed
from the entire train.

829
00:39:44,320 --> 00:39:45,320
(CHOKING)

830
00:39:46,240 --> 00:39:49,560
We hope you have enjoyed
your journey on the Orient Express.

831
00:39:49,800 --> 00:39:51,000
I take it you know a way out?

832
00:39:51,080 --> 00:39:53,000
My enemy's enemy is my friend.

833
00:39:53,080 --> 00:39:55,040
Especially when he
has a built-in teleporter.

834
00:39:55,120 --> 00:39:56,240
Great! So use it!

835
00:39:56,600 --> 00:39:58,880
-A little more work.
-Doctor!

836
00:39:59,080 --> 00:40:00,840
Couple of minutes max.

837
00:40:01,400 --> 00:40:02,840
-I'll give you a shout.
-(CLARA THUDS)

838
00:40:22,720 --> 00:40:24,320
Oh, hello, again. Sleep well?

839
00:40:24,920 --> 00:40:26,720
Weren't we just on a train?

840
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:28,360
Oh, that was ages ago.

841
00:40:30,280 --> 00:40:31,480
And?

842
00:40:31,560 --> 00:40:32,840
And what?

843
00:40:33,640 --> 00:40:35,600
Oh, and, uh, we got off the train.

844
00:40:36,880 --> 00:40:38,920
Oh, well, the teleporter
worked eventually.

845
00:40:39,040 --> 00:40:41,280
Beamed everyone into the Tardis.
No casualties.

846
00:40:41,360 --> 00:40:43,400
Just a bevy of sleeping beauties.

847
00:40:43,800 --> 00:40:47,080
I tried hacking Gus from the Tardis
to find out who set this all up.

848
00:40:47,160 --> 00:40:48,520
He really didn't like that.

849
00:40:49,040 --> 00:40:51,320
Set off some fail-safe thing.

850
00:40:52,440 --> 00:40:53,440
Blew up the train.

851
00:40:54,640 --> 00:40:57,080
-Blew up the train?
-Blew up the train.

852
00:40:58,120 --> 00:40:59,440
But we got away.

853
00:41:00,080 --> 00:41:02,200
I dropped everyone off
at the nearest civilised planet,

854
00:41:02,280 --> 00:41:03,800
which happened to be here.

855
00:41:03,920 --> 00:41:06,680
And you seemed happy asleep
so I just left you.

856
00:41:10,080 --> 00:41:11,440
So you saved everyone?

857
00:41:13,800 --> 00:41:16,720
No, I just saved you
and I let everyone else suffocate.

858
00:41:16,800 --> 00:41:17,800
(MOCK LAUGH)

859
00:41:18,080 --> 00:41:20,920
-Hmm.
-Yeah, this is just my cover story.

860
00:41:22,360 --> 00:41:26,080
So when you lied to Maisie,
when you made me lie to Maisie...

861
00:41:26,160 --> 00:41:28,600
I couldn't risk Gus
finding out my plan and stopping me.

862
00:41:28,760 --> 00:41:31,160
So you were pretending to be heartless?

863
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:43,800
Would you like to think that about me?
Would that make it easier?

864
00:41:46,200 --> 00:41:49,200
I didn't know if I could save her.

865
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:53,040
I couldn't save Quell,
I couldn't save Moorhouse.

866
00:41:53,200 --> 00:41:55,840
There was a good chance
that she'd die, too.

867
00:41:57,960 --> 00:41:59,480
At which point

868
00:42:00,360 --> 00:42:01,840
I would have just

869
00:42:03,280 --> 00:42:05,040
moved onto the next

870
00:42:05,480 --> 00:42:06,880
and the next

871
00:42:07,080 --> 00:42:08,400
until I beat it.

872
00:42:10,520 --> 00:42:13,200
Sometimes, the only choices
you have are bad ones.

873
00:42:14,200 --> 00:42:15,800
But you still have to choose.

874
00:42:25,600 --> 00:42:26,640
(CHUCKLES)

875
00:42:26,720 --> 00:42:29,640
It's, uh, quite a vehicle
you have here, Doctor.

876
00:42:30,360 --> 00:42:32,480
I won't pretend
to understand half of it.

877
00:42:33,200 --> 00:42:34,200
Having said that,

878
00:42:34,280 --> 00:42:37,320
I did notice you've got a couple
of drive stacks need replacing.

879
00:42:37,400 --> 00:42:38,720
Oh, you did, did you?

880
00:42:38,800 --> 00:42:40,880
Yeah. You should get someone in.

881
00:42:41,200 --> 00:42:43,240
And a job like that takes forever.

882
00:42:43,880 --> 00:42:45,080
Really?

883
00:42:45,480 --> 00:42:47,400
Well, I suppose whoever I did get in,

884
00:42:47,480 --> 00:42:50,600
might just be easier to have them
stay on board for a while.

885
00:42:51,520 --> 00:42:53,880
I don't suppose you'd know of anyone?

886
00:42:57,480 --> 00:42:58,520
No.

887
00:42:58,640 --> 00:43:00,960
Sorry, Doctor, but I don't think I do.

888
00:43:02,240 --> 00:43:03,800
That job could, uh,

889
00:43:04,560 --> 00:43:05,800
change a man.

890
00:43:05,880 --> 00:43:08,040
Yes, it does. Frequently.

891
00:43:09,800 --> 00:43:12,840
Well, I won't keep you.
Goodbye, Perkins.

892
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:14,880
Good to meet you.

893
00:43:14,960 --> 00:43:18,240
You, too, Doctor. And, uh, good luck.

894
00:43:28,360 --> 00:43:29,880
(DOOR CLOSES)

895
00:43:31,840 --> 00:43:33,000
Do you love it?

896
00:43:34,760 --> 00:43:35,800
Love what?

897
00:43:37,120 --> 00:43:39,560
I know it's scary and difficult

898
00:43:39,960 --> 00:43:42,760
but do you love being the man
making the impossible choice?

899
00:43:42,840 --> 00:43:43,880
Why would I?

900
00:43:43,960 --> 00:43:45,400
Because it's what you do.

901
00:43:45,480 --> 00:43:46,920
All day, every day.

902
00:43:48,040 --> 00:43:50,280
-It's my life.
-Doesn't have to be.

903
00:43:53,120 --> 00:43:54,600
Is it like...

904
00:43:57,800 --> 00:43:58,880
Like what?

905
00:44:02,960 --> 00:44:04,040
An addiction?

906
00:44:04,240 --> 00:44:06,400
Well, you can't really tell
if something's an addiction

907
00:44:06,480 --> 00:44:07,600
till you try and give it up.

908
00:44:09,080 --> 00:44:10,480
And you never have.

909
00:44:12,280 --> 00:44:14,360
Let me know how it goes.

910
00:44:14,680 --> 00:44:16,040
(MOBILE RINGING)

911
00:44:22,520 --> 00:44:24,440
Hey, Danny. How are you?

912
00:44:25,080 --> 00:44:26,280
DANNY: I'm fine.

913
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:28,120
So is it done?

914
00:44:29,320 --> 00:44:31,680
Yep. Mission accomplished.

915
00:44:31,920 --> 00:44:34,920
Listen, I can't talk now
but I'll see you soon and, um...

916
00:44:37,640 --> 00:44:38,760
I love you.

917
00:44:38,960 --> 00:44:40,560
I love you, too.

918
00:44:40,960 --> 00:44:43,960
Huh. No accounting for taste.

919
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:46,240
Okay, see you soon.

920
00:44:50,840 --> 00:44:52,480
Was that Danny? What did he want?

921
00:45:00,640 --> 00:45:01,960
He's fine with it.

922
00:45:03,760 --> 00:45:05,560
-Sorry, I...
-Danny. He's fine!

923
00:45:05,640 --> 00:45:07,360
With the idea of me and you
knocking about.

924
00:45:07,440 --> 00:45:10,080
It was his idea that we stop
but he's decided he doesn't mind

925
00:45:10,160 --> 00:45:11,160
and neither do I.

926
00:45:11,240 --> 00:45:13,240
Oh, to hell with the last hurrah,
let's keep going!

927
00:45:13,360 --> 00:45:16,640
-That's a big change of heart.
-Yeah, they happen.

928
00:45:16,720 --> 00:45:17,800
Seriously?

929
00:45:17,880 --> 00:45:19,680
Look, as long as you get me home safe

930
00:45:19,800 --> 00:45:21,280
and on time, everything is great.

931
00:45:21,360 --> 00:45:23,280
I am so sorry. I've had a wobble.

932
00:45:23,360 --> 00:45:24,840
It's a big wobble but it's fine.

933
00:45:24,920 --> 00:45:26,920
Forget about it.
Now, shut up and give me some planets.

934
00:45:27,040 --> 00:45:28,840
Well, I'm glad that you said that,

935
00:45:28,920 --> 00:45:31,080
because you know that one
that's made entirely of shrubs?

936
00:45:31,160 --> 00:45:33,720
-Are you sure about this?
-Are you? Have you ever been sure?

937
00:45:34,160 --> 00:45:35,200
No.

938
00:45:35,720 --> 00:45:37,320
Then what are you waiting for?

939
00:45:39,760 --> 00:45:40,760
Let's go.

940
00:45:45,160 --> 00:45:47,160
Oh, that can't be good.

941
00:45:47,240 --> 00:45:49,880
DOCTOR: Something nearby is leaching
all the external dimensions.

942
00:45:49,960 --> 00:45:50,960
CLARA: Aliens?
DOCTOR: Possibly.

943
00:45:51,040 --> 00:45:52,200
Oh, who am I kidding? Probably.

944
00:45:52,320 --> 00:45:54,480
Whatever they are,
they're experimenting.

945
00:45:54,560 --> 00:45:57,160
They're testing, they are...
They are dissecting.

946
00:45:57,480 --> 00:45:59,920
Trying to understand us,
trying to understand

947
00:46:00,040 --> 00:46:01,040
three dimensions.

948
00:46:01,240 --> 00:46:03,080
Life support failing. (ECHOING)

